  "en_notes_asad": [
    {
      "note_no": "7",
      "note": "The Lisan al-Arab gives \"the calyx (kimm) of the grape before its flowering\" as the primary significance of kafur; according to other lexicologists (e.g\" Taj al-'Arus), it denotes \"the calyx of any flower\"; Jawhari applies it to the \"spathe of a palm tree\", Hence, this - and not \"camphor\" - is evidently the meaning of kafur in the above context: an allusion to the sweet, extremely delicate fragrance of the symbolic \"drink\" 'of divine knowledge (cf. 83:25-28 and the corresponding notes 8 and 9)."
